  "primaryContentSections": [
    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "When using your app on an iOS device, users are likely to move in and out of range of Wi-Fi, switching to cellular networks and back again."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Multipath TCP improves the performance of your app when a user is in a location with limited Wi-Fi and while their device is transitioning to and from cellular data usage. In its default configuration, a URL session uses a single radio for a network call, preferring Wi-Fi over cellular. However, with Multipath TCP enabled, the URL session initiates the request on both radios and selects the more responsive of the two with a preference for Wi-Fi."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": 3,
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Enable Multipath TCP in Your App",
          "anchor": "2930782"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "These steps are required:"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "unorderedList",
          "items": [
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": "Enable the "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/bundleresources/entitlements/com_apple_developer_networking_multipath"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " in the Xcode Capabilities pane for your app target."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": "Set the "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/foundation/nsurlsessionconfiguration/2875967-multipathservicetype"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " property in "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/foundation/nsurlsessionconfiguration"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " to a mode other than "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "codeVoice",
                      "code": "none"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": ". For most cases, the handover mode is the best option. This mode provides your users with a seamless transition between Wi-Fi and cellular, allowing uninterrupted usage of your app. (For information about other modes, see "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/foundation/nsurlsessionmultipathservicetype"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": ".)"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": []
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "While the user’s device is connected to a reliable Wi-Fi network, your app uses only Wi-Fi, and no cellular data is consumed. As the user leaves the range of the Wi-Fi network and the signal starts to deteriorate, Multipath TCP begins transitioning data usage to the cellular network to provide a seamless transition."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "aside",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "Multipath TCP requires the destination server to have Multipath TCP enabled. Many commercial load balancers already support Multipath TCP, and you can enable it in the configuration. For Linux-based servers, the Linux kernel with Multipath TCP is available at the "
                },
                {
                  "type": "link",
                  "title": "Multipath TCP",
                  "destination": "https://multipath-tcp.org"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": " website."
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "style": "important"
        },
        {
          "level": 3,
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Limitations when Using Multipath TCP with Wi-Fi Assist",
          "anchor": "2923118"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Because Wi-Fi Assist is a user selectable, device-wide option, there are a few limitations when using Multipath TCP with that option enabled:"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "unorderedList",
          "items": [
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": "Wi-Fi Assist prevents flows from using cellular data when your app is in the background."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": "Wi-Fi Assist limits the amount of data that your app can send over cellular networks. When the limit is reached, Multipath TCP is disabled."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Wi-Fi Assist is integrated into the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/foundation/nsurlsession"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " API and doesn’t require any changes to the session configuration. At the start of each URL session task, Wi-Fi Assist determines whether to use Wi-Fi or cellular data for the connection."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "After the URL session task begins, Wi-Fi Assist doesn’t change from Wi-Fi to cellular or from cellular to Wi-Fi. Multipath TCP extends the performance-improving capabilities of Wi-Fi Assist to provide seamless radio transition and improved throughput."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "aside",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "When using a developer-enabled device for testing, you can disable the Wi-Fi Assist data limitation in the developer section of the Settings app."
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "style": "note",
          "name": "Note"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": []
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": []
        }
      ]
    }
